Use these rules throughout the project.

Architecture rules
Never mix application code and deployment manifests
Never deploy directly from CI to Kubernetes
Never bypass GitOps repository
Always treat GitOps repo as the deployment source of truth
Simplicity rules
Prefer clarity over cleverness
Avoid unnecessary abstraction
Avoid adding tools not explicitly required
Avoid “enterprise fantasy” features
Interview rules

Everything you implement must answer:

Why does this exist?
What problem does it solve?
What would break if removed?
What are the trade-offs?

If you cannot explain it simply → it should not exist.

⚙️ CODING RULES (КОД И КОНФИГИ)
General
Write clean, readable, production-style code
Use clear naming
Avoid magic values
Avoid hardcoding environment-specific values
Docker
Use minimal base images
Use proper layering
Avoid unnecessary packages
Keep images small
Kubernetes
Always include:
readinessProbe
livenessProbe
resource requests and limits
Avoid overcomplicated manifests
Use labels consistently
Helm
Keep templates readable
Do not overuse templating tricks
Use values.yaml properly
Separate environments via values files
🔐 SECURITY RULES
Never store secrets in code
Assume secrets come from CI/CD or Kubernetes
Avoid printing sensitive data in logs
Avoid insecure defaults
🔁 CI/CD RULES (GitLab)
Pipeline must be deterministic
Use clear stages:
test
build
publish
gitops update
Do not mix responsibilities between stages
Use environment variables properly
Do not hardcode credentials
🔄 GITOPS RULES (ArgoCD)
ArgoCD pulls from Git, never from CI
Git defines desired state
Changes happen via commits
No manual kubectl apply in final design
